Customizable card caddy to organize cards for all your favorite board games.

The included STL file is just one example of the output that can be created. Note that the Thingiverse Customizer app doesn't prompt for all possible tweakable values in this model, so you may have to edit the SCAD file manually and render into an STL yourself via OpenSCAD.

So far I have used this to make caddies for:

  • Tokaido

Update

New piece added to complement the small rect 25mm pieces.

Almost all terrain pieces look better if you add a base to them. Sure, you can carve out a base from MDF (wear a mask) or cardboard (it will warp) or some kind of plastic (not easy to come by good materials, or expensive). Why not 3D print them?

This is a set of modular terrain bases. Piece together any base you can imagine. Glue it together on top of a thin paper. Then you can texture them, paint them and decorate the terrain much better.

In the photos I have used three other terrain pieces from thingiverse. Here they are:

A case for the Parallella Board with fan mount. This requires 12V power and some soldering experience.

Please note that this case is specifically made for a 12V power supply, a 5V Voltage Regulator and a 50mm 12V fan (see the Parallella Quick Start Guide: "The board gets hot and needs a fan to operate reliably over extended periods."). This was designed in Solidworks and I printed it with PLA on my Makergear M2. As you can see, I've purposely blocked the 5V power jack on the Parallella to prevent plugging the 12V power supply into the 5V power jack. WARNING: THIS TUTORIAL INVOLVES SOLDERING DIRECTLY TO YOUR PARALLELLA BOARD. FOLLOW AT YOUR OWN RISK. For this build, I've used the following hardware:
  • A 5V 3A Voltage Regulator
  • A 2.5mm DC barrel jack connector
  • A 50mm fan
  • A 12V 3A DC Power Supply
  • 4x 4mm M3 screws for mounting Parallella
  • 4x 12mm M3 screws for mounting fan in lid
  • 4x M3 hex nuts
  • 2.54mm JST connectors
  • Some additional wire for connecting the DC power inside of the case
  • A soldering iron & solder
  • Double-sided tape for mounting voltage regulator
    • BEFORE YOU SOLDER, BE SURE TO CHECK VOLTAGE POLARITY OF YOUR WIRES TO AVOID FRYING YOUR ELECTRONICS
  • Solder the JST connector to the back of the 5V jack on the Parallella Board (see picture in gallery for details)
  • Solder the fan & voltage regulator to the external DC power Jack (which is center positive, use a multimeter to confirm the lead on the back side).
  • Use a multimeter to ensure that all of your solder joints were done correctly.
  • Mount the fan to the inside of the lid with the 12mm M3 screws & nuts. Mount the voltage regulator with double sided tape. Mount the barrel jack with the included nut.
  • Snap the case together and power up the electronics with the external 12V power supply.
    • You don't have to use the exact parts that I used in this build, but I chose parts that I've tested in other projects and are inexpensive. Please leave feedback or let me know if you want any changes done. I might upload a second version without a fan that allows you to connect a 5V power supply directly to the Parallella, but I think it's best to have a fan running on this thing all the time to avoid burning it out.

description.text:
I made this box with a secret chamber for the "Cipher Ring V4" (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2706672) from @osj1961.

The cipher ring fits very well and tightly. If you take out the ring, you can also remove the centre part (core) of the box by a short turn. You can place a secret message or the decoding key in it.

I made the cipher ring and this box, as well as a multi-part encrypted riddle as a Christmas present. My nephews had to find out the password for a cryptex in several steps. One of the steps was to find the secret chamber where there were further hints.

title: Flash Grids for Bolt VC-310 / Neewer NW320 / Meike MK320
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Bolt VC-310 Speedlight or "Flash" from B&H (aka Neewer NW320 or Meike MK320 from others) is a small versatile flash that is great for more compact mirror-less cameras, but accessories such as "grids" for it are impossible to find.

This "thing" is a grid light modifier that easily and securely clips onto the flash the same way the factory included diffuser does. The grid is made of hexagons at 5mm pitch with 0.8mm walls. Thinner walls were impossible to properly slice in Cura. If you want to learn more about grids etc check out this webpage.

The STL files are available in 7.5, 10, 20, 30 and 40mm grid depths for choice of spot size. The 40mm grid may be a little excessive. Most people will want the 10 and 20mm size (see attached images taken with 10, 20 and 40mm grids using 34mm equivalent focal length @ 8ft). I tried a 5mm depth grid but it had a ugly ring of light around it. I may try to experiment with more sizes.

UPDATE Jan-4 2018:

I had previously left 2mm of space between the grid and the flash face. I've now added a gel holder design that can be placed in there (see photos). I printed a bunch and used a glue stick to attach the gel films, and then trim around it with a good pair of scissors. You could could probably just tuck one in and use this gel holder to retain it.

Printer:

Craftbot 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

N/A

Notes:

PETG works fairly well. I don't think PLA would be a good choice as the flash can get warm from use and the camera bag in the car could also. Obviously use neutral opaque colors.
I needed to "de-fuzz" the PETG. I cleaned out the holes with a handheld 5/32 drill bit, then used a heat gun on low to carefully melt/fuse the remaining peach fuzz.

I started with a flatbed scan of the flash diffuser for dimensions and shape and mapped the image onto a plane. I used a b-spline curve to reproduce the complex curves of one side and mirrored it. Probably overkill in retrospect. Then I created a 2-D offset sketch (manually!) to create the necessary draft angles on all sides, then shifted it 18mm higher and lofted the two. The I extruded the 2nd sketch further in height to hold the gird array plus 2mm in height.

I used the part WB primitive wizard to make a hexagon mapped to the face of the grid tube extrusion, then reverse extruded the hexagon to the desired grid depth. Then I made a shell with the "thickness" tool, then in Draft WB made a 2 column hex array, then another array to fill the grid area. The array was then clipped using the boolean overlap of the array and the grid tube extrusion.

I fused the base and grid tube extrusion and used the "thickness" tool in "pipe" settings to make a open ended shell. I then fused the grid array, shell, latches and ribs.

FreeCAD can be a little buggy, I was unable to change the depth of the grid with everything fused. If you want to change that, you will need to delete the fuse, change the gridtube and hexagon extrusion lengths, and then re-fuse. Also the fillet won't work on corners sharper than 90deg, so the back is chamfered instead.

title: Case to use Miracle Box MB-100(CCTV) on 3D printer

description.text:
(English)
I needed an IP camera to keep up with my printer.
The wifi cameras I found at a good price had very low resolution, (640x480).
I ended up finding the mb-100 miraclebox that works at 1080x720x30fps (no audio) over wired network.
As my router is next to my printer, I bought this used camera.
This model is not very good for fixing to the printer, due to the size of the case, but the camera itself is very small, as you can see in the photos.
So I printed the box to mount the camera and fix it to the printer.
I used the 12V feed from the ramps to the camera.
It works relatively well, now I need to find a better place to fix it.
Since the camera has an IR, I can monitor the printer's work in the dark.

more projects on my youtube channel
https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLdgpqnxni6cPqBRCllahNwBReu3VwxgBX

(Portuguese)
Eu precisava de uma camera IPpara acompanhar o funcionamento da minha impressora.
As cameras wifi que encontrei com um bom preço tinham resolução muito baixa, (640x480).
Acabei encontrando a miraclebox mb-100 que funciona a 1080x720x30fps (sem audio) por rede com fio.
Como meu roteador fica próximo à minha impressora, comprei essa camera usada.
Este modelo não é muito bom para fixar na impressora, por conta do tamanho da case, mas a camera em si é bem pequena, como se nota nas fotos.
Assim, imprimi a caixa para montar a camera e fixar na impressora.
Utilizei a própria alimentação de 12v da ramps para a camera.
Funciona relativamente bem, agora preciso acha um lugar melhor para fixá-la.
Como a camera tem IR posso acompanhar o trabalho da impressora até no escuro.

mais projetos no meu canal do youtube:
https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLdgpqnxni6cPqBRCllahNwBReu3VwxgBX

Did anyone get a Grip6 (Grip6.com) belt for Cristmas? If you did you might notice its difficult to hang on a standard belt hook. They sell a hanger on their website, but we have 3D printers so here is my version.

The hook has a 35mm id which fits my closet perfectly. Other closets may vary.

My hanger is enough for two belts, so you might be compelled to buy a second for balance. Please know I am not associated, affiliated, nor receive any compensation for anything you may do.

description.text:
I created this tile and tray set for our 3rd-grade program - Cultural Astronomy: China.
We look at for great inventions from China:

  1. The Compass
  2. Fireworks (Gunpowder)
  3. Papermaking (using wood pulp)
  4. Printing Press

We use the tile set and tray to demonstrate how the printing press was done. Six of the ten included tiles are chosen to be placed in the tray. Ink is then applied onto the raised characters and paper is placed on top, and pressed down. This simple innovation on the idea of stamping made for an enormous breakthrough in the sharing of knowledge.

author: Nemermj

title: Samsung Galaxy S8 Plus Cell Phone Camera Mount Kit

description.text:
This is a super mixed file set specifically designed for a Galaxy S8 Plus phone with an OtterBox Defender case.

The actual tripod is a mix that includes ideas from the ppet36 iPhone Tripod and the Cell Phone Tripod by sthone. In this mix, I used the beefed up parts from stone but did some rounding to the actual phone mount. I then modified the tripod legs to use the rounded tips that the ppet36 model included.

For the tripod, I used a 8/32 x 2" Socket Head Cap Screw and Wing Nut to assemble it. You can use a rubber band to secure the phone to the mount if needed. However, it fits pretty snugly on the Galaxy S8 Plus phone with an OtterBox Defender case.

Quite often, one may only need a simple stand for the S8 cell phone camera. As such,I also include a remix of the Universal Cell Phone Camera Tripod Mount by T_om. In my remix, I slot the mount to again fit a Galaxy S8 Plus phone with an OtterBox Defender case. I also rounded and angled some corners to use less filament and to give it a little less blocky look. Please note that this mount prints with a 1/4"x20 female thread so it may be directly attached to standard tripod thumb screws.

The slot on both mounts is 13.8mm (.54 inches) wide. As such, it may fit many other cell phone models with cases installed. For example, it fits my Galaxy Note 4 with UAG case.

I've included my gcode file for my CR-10 printer. If you have a smaller build plate, you may have to rotate the 212mm (8.35 inches) long design 45% to fit diagonally on the build plate.

The Lulzbot Mini has a rectangular arm for holding the filament spool. The spool drags on the arm and causes a jerky motion of the spool. Others have designed spool holders for the Mini to alleviate this problem. Here is my version. The bolt is a ⅜ x 5” hex bolt. The Mounting bracket replaces the standard Mini arm. The cylinder is two parts glued together.

The friction is very low, so the unit is very smooth in operation. The spool will even roll back when the head rises. The shoulder on the cylinder will fit through the holes of all the brands of filament I have tried, and requires no fastening or tightening of the cylinder to the filament spool. Everything is free floating. I used PLA.

description.text:
These should fit on an aluminium 25mm tube clamps used to fix a carbon fibre motor mount on a tube arm. Their length was determined by the style/size of carbon fibre plate used.

So the width of the clamps determines the width of the landing gear plate, and the length of the motor mount determines the length of the landing gear plate which is 32.5mm and 52mm respectively

Although the pictured motor mount can take 16mm, 22mm and 25mm tube clamps, these landing gear have only been designed for the 25mm size.

You fix the landing gear below the motor mount by bolting with the same M3 bolts and Locknuts used on the aluminium tube clamp. So no extra hardware and only the landing gear themselves add any additional weight.

Even though these are only 80mm long and weight 12g, they still keep my 1200mm quad X with 22'' blades from touching the ground whilst landing 30 degrees off flat (a very bad landing). They're also useful for taking off from grass :)

Printer:

Anet A6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

40%

Notes:

@40% infill they are just a hair over 12grams per leg, so around 48g for all 4. Increasing the infill should strengthen them without adding too much to the weight.

I designed them in "DesignSpark Mechanical", and this is the first time I have ever done a 3d design so I'm sure they can be improved. Feel free to use the included .RSDOC file to make modifications, just share any improvements :)

Also, as a newbie, I'm keen to learn, so if any of you veteran designers have any tips or comments please speak!

I can print the midsection reinforcement spans with my cheap and cheerful Anet A6 extrusion printer without supports. I still get a few strands that don't quite affix correctly but this doesn't seem to affect the strength. So you can print without supports etc and just trim a bit as necessary.

Example 25mm aluminium tube clamp Example carbon fibre motor mount with aluminium tube mounts Installed landing gear. For scale I'm using a 5030 300KV motor and 22'' carbon blades. Close up of installation.

title: SPANNERHANDS small volume remix

description.text:
Spannerhands original model is great, but as I'm always overthinking things, I ended doing some mods to the small volume 1kg version.
So the mods:

  • added brackets for M3 nuts and bolts for tightening the base and lid parts together. I don't trust glue but that's just me :)
  • added M3 nut indents to the brackets that need screws. Easier to assemble
  • added printable M8 bolt and nuts. Debatable if this is great or not, seems to be working even though the bolt bends. Probably need to print with high infill
  • PTFE nozzle with 4mm hole, for M5 thread PTFE coupler
  • work in progress cores that use airsoft pellets as bearings

Got few of these printed and seems to be working great. The cores are WIP.

TODO: maybe windows, and 750g version...

title: Raspberry Pi Header Cap
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a snap-on cap for the standard Raspberry Pi header in case you want to run the pi naked but worry about something shorting all those easy-to-drop-stuff-on header pins. Sure you could just cut off an old connector or print something with a buncha holes. But then you gotta line up all the pins and printing a buncha holes can be a pain. This just snaps in place over top of the whole assembly. Has little cutouts on either side for clearance in case you have a baseplate screwed onto the bottom.

This is an actual-dimensions file - meaning it's not scaled to compensate for material shrink or a poorly calibrated printer. You'll need to scale accordingly if those are issues for ya.

description.text:
This is an evolution of my previous model: Batisfera Sketch

Print this model only if you know how to setup the supports and remove them carefully.

The model has holes in the elements for connection, and by scaling the connectors you can adjust joints tolerance. Connectors has 80% scale by default. Use drop of a glue to fix the joints, in any case.
(full connector/hole size is 10x4x2mm, with 100% scale, in case you need to know)

The wheels in the split model are floating "in the air" to have better layers pattern/specular after a print. Of course, the supports are necessary.

So in general, you need to print one of each:

  • batisfera_body_optimized_repaired.stl
  • batisfera_wheels_optimized_repaired.stl
  • batisfera_jointsScale80_x5_repaired.stl (or batisfera_jointsScale90_x5_repaired.stl)

Good luck!

Like it? Print it! Share it!

Want to see more models? Press the TIP Designer button! Every $ will be spent on a pizza for another sleepless night, when a new model is born! Thanks in advance!

Update 2018-01-04:

  • joints x5 in 80% scale added, looks like they fit much better than 90% version
  • single joint model in 90% scale removed, scale and use 100% model instead
  • full set model removed

Update 2018-01-02:

  • complete joints rebuild, now it will be possible to adjust joints tolerance
  • single joint model available, in 100% scale (scale down manually to fit the holes in the joints)
  • single joint model added, in 90% scale (by default)
  • full set model added, with all needed elements in one file

Update 2018-01-01:

  • solid model updated - it was not optimized version, sorry

Update 2017-12-31:

  • my first test showed, that the joints are pretty bad, and I need to improve them. So wait for the updates!

I've been wanting to get rid of the external controller box on my Tronxy printers since I built the first one. I now have four of the X3A printers and the controller box takes up too much room and moving the printers with it attached is not fun either. No reset button access and the power switch is difficult to reach if you place the controller under the printer not to mention the SD card........

The graphic of the whole design needs up dating once I get everything completed. What has changed is the power supply (both the 20 or the 30A) has moved to the outside of the frame due to interference of Z axis stepper mounting bracket. The Melzi controller box now hangs lower so that the separate mounting brackets could be eliminated. The cable box (if used) will need to move to the back of the printer. The Melzi controller is soooooo long! The controller case takes up most of the right side of the printer.

My goal was to be able to re-use as much of the controller box parts as possible. When I designed the Ultimate Tronxy Cooler (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2063696) , I replaced the 40mm stock hot end cooling fan with a 30mm and two 25mm filament cooling fans and re-purposed the 40mm fan to cool the Melzi board (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2031783). The 40mm fan is now mounted to the Melzi box top. You have a choice of a plain top or the Alabama 'A' top (ROLL TIDE!). I printed the Melzi box tops in clear PLA so that the LEDs can shine through. I also used a piece of red 3mm filament as the RESET button extension (1.75mm will work too). What I did was set the filament on the heat bed (70°C) and let it stay while printing. After about 30 minutes the filament will be perfectly straight. I then flattened one end of the filament with a hot soldering iron (~150°C works well). This it the end that will touch the reset button. I then placed the piece of filament in the top from the inside and then placed the top in position on the Melzi box and pushed the filament until it was touching the reset button but was not pressing on it. I then cut off the filament leaving about 4mm extending beyond the top surface. Next I used my soldering iron to flatten that end of the filament. Now the reset extension is captive to the top and simply floats until you push it to reset the controller. FINALLY, access to the reset button!

The kit will consist of the following:

  1. 100mm Legs DONE!

  2. 20 amp AND 30 amp power supply mounts with integrated power switch DONE!

  3. Display controller mount (works with the monorail Y axis or the linear bearing/rod upgrade) DONE!

  4. Melzi controller box with a RESET button! Two fan covers, one plain and one Alabama 'A' Controller is DONE!

  5. A box for hiding all of the cables that would otherwise get in the way. DONE!

Legs are DONE!. They must be printed upside down with support. The hole in the bottom of the leg will allow a leveling screw and pad to come later. The original acrylic "foot" must be removed. Reuse the "foot" screws and boat nuts to attach. It is best to install the bottom screws first and then slide the side boat nuts in from the sides to attach the top portion. These are very strong and support the frame very well.

The two part Melzi controller board box has been re-designed so that no brackets are needed. The two halves are joined using a "finger joint" with super glue. I strongly suggest that you test fit the two parts together and then mount your Melzi board and adjust the box length to fit. Once the board has been mounted the total length is set and you can super glue the two parts together. The reason that you need to do it this way is because these boards vary somewhat in the hole spacing. YMMV

Cable box has been designed. This is optional to hide all of the extra length wiring that is not needed. I figured I could print this in about the same amount of time it would take to shorten all of the wiring.

The power supply mounts are DONE! The power supply has been moved to the outside of the left side of the frame. It does not extend past the X axis motor so very little if any desk top room is lost. Just added the 30A power supply version (which is a good upgrade for the X3).

Display case is DONE! The display board fits perfectly and works with both the Y axis monorail and linear bearing mod (Kencam https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2185364).

All of the PCBs attach with "servo" self threading screws as well as the box tops. Attachment to the frame is with 4x10mm screws and 4mm "boat" nuts.

Design is DONE! All parts have been printed at least twice for checking fitment.
Completed pictures coming soon (printers are busy printing another project).

This has been a fun but challenging project.

Silver printer is done, well almost.....I ran out of wire for the filament cooling fans (more is on the way) but I wanted to show what the finished project looks like. Next will be the black printer and then the red one and then the yellow one will be last. I have ALL of the parts printer for all four of my printers.

Here are some of the other designs I have done for the X3:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2650465
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2061064

Attention: The ball mount in this version is a little bit to tight. So i broke the first print while trying to put it into the mount.
I will add a new version very soon. As an alternative you can sand off the ball and use grease to get it into the mount. => solver in new version (20180104)

Dies ist ein Adapter für dien Siku Control Traktor mit Frontlader um das Siku
standard Frontladerset an zu hängen. Jedoch ist zu beachten dass es nicht sinnvoll ist
die schweren Anbauteile an den Adapter anzuhängen da der Frontlader dafür nicht
ausgelegt ist. Für den betrieb wird ein Nagel und eine M2-Schraube benötigt.
Der Nagel wir durch die oberen 2 Halter gesteckt. Die M2-Schraube kommt in das Loch in der Mitte, hierzu muss dort noch ein Gewinde geschnitten werden, die Schraube dient zum

description.text:
Quick and dirty air raid siren that makes sound that can be heard from distance. Original idea and first design took about 20 minutes and print time was about 4 hours per part. New updated version has dual tone outer so it sounds little diffirent than original. Siren is designed over 2212 quadcopter motor (from crashed Cheerson CX-20) and is running really nice with 3S and 4S batteries. When running it longer time there is possibility that motor runs hot but i have not had that problem. In the bottom there is a 20mm round circles for attaching siren where ever you want, i designed and printed GoPro mount to attach siren in bottom of quadcopter camera mount to have remote controlled flying siren (because who doesn't need one?). When printing outer case we used supports but they are not really needed. We used about 40% infill but that is overkill and lower infill will do just fine, our siren is just extra rugged. We printed this with 0,3 mm resolution, but even lower resolution will do just fine. Prusa original 0.4 nozzle just don't allow us print bigger layer heights.

Please contact me If you have any ideas how to improve or redesign this siren, or even make it work better for your application.

title: Raspberry Pi + Camera Setup for Monoprice MP Mini Delta
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a set of parts to mount a Raspberry pi and a Pi camera to your Monoprice MP Mini Delta. Together with the amazing Octoprint software you can manage, live stream and timelapse your MP Delta, all wirelessly using a web gui!

The Pi mount consists of four arms which latch into the slots on the Mini's verical rails. The other side of each arm screws into the Pi using the standard holes. An "x" baseplate is provided to prevent short-circuits against the case. Fasten the arms and the baseplate to your pi using screws/nuts. The green cap pictured isn't included in this kit but is a part of another thing I created.

The camera mount consists of an arm which is screwed into the base using an existing screw hole (remove the existing screw and install a slightly longer screw). The baseplate mount arm is the exact same height as the baseplate so even if you're doing full-bed prints it won't collide PROVIDED YOU MOUNT IT WITH THE JOINT FACING DOWN. The mount connects to two other jointed sections and a mount for the camera. The arm allows a great deal of motion to handle different build volumes. The camera intentionally does NOT have movement on the ROLL axis. Since the camera is centered on the build plate it doesn't need it.

You can position the arm in a lot of different ways. By collapsing both arms on top of each other the camera can be placed almost baseplate level. By stretching it all the way out you can see the entire vertical print volume. Each of the joints has a countersunk hex socket to make tightning easier.

To set this up you will need:

  • Raspberry Pi http://amzn.to/2CkVG9C
  • Raspberry Pi camera V2 http://amzn.to/2BXnmOo
  • Long flex cable for Pi camera http://amzn.to/2CmnU1r
  • Short USB cable (you have one of these)
  • 4x M2.5x16 screws/nuts for Raspberry Pi
  • 4x M2x8 screws/nuts for Pi Camera (you can get away with 2 - 4 is overkill)
  • 1x M3x16 screw (for attaching camera arm to the base)
  • 3x M3x16 screws/nuts (for the arm joints)
    For the screws I just bought an assortment pack: http://amzn.to/2Cqf8j1
    optional: Gooseneck usb LED lights (I used Ikea Jansjo lights. )

All of the parts are sized so they will print just fine on the mini. I was able to print most of them without supports although the arms with the countersunk sockets benefitted from small supports. Print them at 70% or better and 0.2mm layer height since some of the parts are kinda thin. You'll need to print each of the Pi mount arms and the extension arm twice to make your kit. All of the parts print correctly on the Delta but you'll need to fill the bed twice.

description.text:
I designed a blow dart gun that is about 3.3 feet long and is modular. The design consists of 4 parts that all screw together to create a working blow dart gun. Also towards the top and final layers of the threading, the object can start to wobble causing there to be like 0.25 inches of messed up threading. Just cute that part off and sand the inside and you should be fine. Inside the blow dart gun when it is being printed there can be some oozing so make sure to sand the inside to have as little imperfections as possible for less friction. I will include the link to the darts I bought. The darts do not fit inside if the print shrinks so I recommend to cut a little bit off the end of the dart.

title: Steering Wheel Spinner Knob for 29x36 mm Wheel

description.text:
My wife had sholder surgery, and needed an assist for many months. The original by FULspeed wouldn't fit our steering wheel, so I modified the original files to fit the non-round, 29 x 36 mm steering wheel in my Pontiac. I changed the knob pivot bolt to a 5/16 carriage bolt and modified the knob and cap so a nylon lock nut would fit within the cavity. I also used sheet metal screws threaded into the bottom half rather than metric thru-bolts and nuts.
It really made things easier for my wife, and I find it useful too. My thanks to FULspeed.

As mentioned in other Things like this, the question of legality and the risk imposed by having this attached to the steering wheel is borne by the user.

Notes:

At the time I printed this, I used ABS to handle the summer heat. Today, I'd consider using high temp PLA, although ABS does have the advantage of being slippery when it runs against another ABS surface. Its been in-place over a year and has been very serviceable.

You will need a 5/16 inch carriage bolt of TBD length, two nylon locking nuts for the bolt, and one washer. I don't believe there is room for a washer in the cap. The other washer and bolt go at the top of the frame, under the knob base (after the supports are broken away from under the knob). You will also need a couple screws for the outside of the assembly. I probably used #6 sheet metal screws. Machine screws can also be used, but the one or both side may have to be drilled out.

title: Bluray, PS3 and PS4 game case stand (extensible)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Needed proper way to store my Bluray discs and wanted to try to design an stand for them. Behold, this. Holds minimum 6 discs, maximum don't know. I guess few hundreds or thousand, depending how well the plastic holds up :)

One goal I had in mind was that it should be extensible. Also preferably no screws and no glue needed. Both goals succeeded, although glue wouldn't hurt when building a larger stand.

The one I've built has now over 100 discs loaded, with room for 20+ more. And to go beyond that, I'll just print more parts. The thing is sturdy enough to tolerate lifting by myself, but it's evident that adding more discs will cause something to break quite soon. Still, I'm positively surprised how rigid it is.

What to print? First, select beams you want to print, 6 and 9 slot beams are available. Let me know if other options are needed.

For the bare minimum stand:

  • 1x stand2_foot_left.stl
  • 1x stand2_foot_right.stl
  • 2x stand2_plate_left.stl
  • 2x stand2_plate_right.stl
  • 1x stand2_side_beamX_left_slots.stl
  • 1x stand2_side_beamX_right_slots.stl
  • 1x stand2_back_beam_X.stl
  • 2x stand2_end_cap.stl
  • 1x stand2_end_cap_back.stl

To extend the stand upwards, print more:

  • stand2_side_beamX_left_slots.stl
  • stand2_side_beamX_right_slots.stl
  • stand2_back_beam_X.stl
  • stand2_plate_left.stl
  • stand2_plate_right.stl

To extend the stand sideways, print:

  • stand2_foot_joined.stl (one per column)
  • stand2_plate_joined.stl (one per column per beam count + 1)
  • stand2_side_beamX_middle.stl (one per column per beam count)
  • stand2_back_beam_X.stl (one per column per beam count)
  • 1x stand2_end_cap.stl
  • 1x stand2_end_cap_back.stl

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

No

Yes

Notes:

I used 2 perimeters, 5% infill, 0.2mm. Printed with PLA. The part tolerances are tuned to my Prusa MK2.

To check how well the parts fit, first print the testparts.stl. If the parts are too tight or too loose, use slicers horizontal compensation feature if available. Don't use scaling, it might skew the overall dimensions too much.

Assembly

Should be quite self evident, but here are some quick notes:

  • feet are at the bottom (doh) and they just clip together. Assemble them first
  • right after feet comes first plate 'layer'. Assemble to plates together to create whole layer and fit it on the feet, taking care to put it on right way. It should go only one way
  • you might need to use file/knife to ease the parts together depending of the print quality
  • after the plate is relatively well in place, install the beams. Take care to install the beams in proper positions. Depending how tight the prints are, you might need to use some force. I used rubber hammer to force some of the parts together :). Nothing even broke, which was bit of a surprise...
  • go on until all plates and beams are in place. Finish the build by installing the end caps on top
  • if parts missing, print them :)

Used OpenSCAD. Source available here: https://github.com/spegelius/3DModels/tree/master/Bluray_stand
Whole thing should be configurable for DVD or other use by changing the dimensions.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Updated 1045EST 01JAN2018 removed bottom panel text so you could place your own.

Another modified dice tray from my former vanilla design at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2490052

Graphics on this dice tray are derived from the following sources:

The stylized fleur-de-lis are my own concoction as a tribute to R.W. Chambers for his overt Francophilia in his writings.

The Voronoi template was selected to represent the foam of the cosmos and spaces in-between - it was derived from Free DXF Files and...

The Yellow Sign is is the creation of Kevin Ross http://kinginyellow.wikia.com/wiki/The_Yellow_Sign_(the_symbol). It is unknown whether The Yellow Sign is copyright Kevin Ross, Chaosium or any other party, if it is copyrighted at all, or some other licences or not? Having emailed Chaosium some time ago to ask and having received no reply I'll take the chance in using it here with no intent to make profit, infringe on anyone's property or profit. Until told otherwise I will just leave this here. Please respect the licence I have chosen to apply.

For the bottom font I used - Ambrosia Regular by Typographer Mediengestaltung http://steffmann.1001fonts.com/ Feel free to make your own quote and use your own preferred font.

Done up in a nice ply or wood and not MDF or HDF, then stained or laquered, I'm certain this would make a fetching gift for family, friends, yourself or a denizen of the Outer Void that favours how you might taste. Test copy cut on MDF pictured above.

Formatted for cutting on the top half of 6mm MDF cut to (Arch C) 24" x 18" sized sheet, which fits across the bed of an Epilog Helix. Duplicate the graphics to fill the sheet or rotate the sheet 180 degrees to cut another tray. All my patterns are designed for cutting at 300dpi. I have provided the PDF and SVG files that I converted online at https://cloudconvert.com/vsd-to-svg. Designed with Visio and PhotoShop. Shared as is.

If you are inclined to be more than a taker and a consumer, pay forward by contributing to this site, as so many others have before you, or perform a random act of kindness, or donate to a good cause when the opportunity next arises. If you liked it enough to download it I'd appreciate a LIKE, it helps get the word out and spread these designs around. That is all.

The clock is always approaching 11:00 in dim Carcosa...

This is a light-box containing 5 pcs. 3d-printed photos created with image to STL software.
To prevent overheating due to lack of ventilation you have to use LED light source ONLY . I suppose that 3W LED is quite enough for photos of maximum thickness 4 mm printed with light colored plastics.

Model includes a G9 lamp socket of original design which is to be used with low power (less then 3W total) LED bulbs. It works good with 220V lamps providing good electrical safety if assembled correctly. I recommend you to use wires of 1 mm thickness to assure it is fixed tight in socket. Line and Neutral are of no matter if you use 220V LED bulb, but you have to check polarity if using a 12V lamp with DC power supply.

To assemble main frame you have to print:
1 x Base
4 x Edge
1 x Top
1 x Top support
1 x G9 socket (you can replace it with your own, but you'll have to think about mounting it on base part).

Also you will need some simple hardware:
11 pcs. M3x10 mm bolts
10 pcs. M3 nuts
G9 LED lightbulb
Some wiring and plastic clamp to fix it onto base part.

To prepare photo I've used an Image to STL converter software. Total thickness of STL has to be no more than 4 mm and size 93x93 mm. You have to combine converted STL with Frame in your slicer to print a 100x100 mm photo which fits this light-box.
Other way is to convert photo to 100x100 mm STL if you are sure that image has dark borders which will have enough thickness to hold it in place.

Notes:

Obviously print the sign in translucent filament. We used ABS. You can scale the whole thing up or down some if desired.

Printing the letters in something like black and gluing them on later is probably better than painting, but there's a 1-piece version if you want to paint it.

The letters probably don't need infill either, but I'd use 10% or so for the mount.

Simplify 3D's gap fill did a great job with the thin walls, 3 upper and lower layers and 2 shells. It printed the outer and inner shell and it's gap fill make a thicker bead in the middle for a solid wall. Other software or printers may need to play with tweaking the settings some so that you get a single solid wall instead of 2 detached shells.

Painting Letters

If you choose to print the one-piece version with the painted letters, then you'll probably need to make sure to use paint. Markers don't work on filament because they wick into the gaps and a terrible smudge oozes out from the letters.

I knew that and still tried a marker with horrid results. (fortunately some alcohol cleaned it off).

Gluing Letters

Be careful with the letter orientation. In particular, the "O" isn't symmetrical. So make sure they look right before gluing.

Obviously the glue/solvent depends on the material you print with. We printed in ABS, so used MEK (not recommended because it's nasty).

Note that the solvent makes it easy to smear the black letters onto the translucent sign, so be careful not to smudge them.
Check out the source thing for more info, including the sketchup file used for the signs.

description.text:
It's a top part to turn your old pipe of cardboard into a rocket launcher for New Year's Eve!

But please be careful and think of your eyes. Try to protect them and the rest of your face!

Printer:

Anet A8

No

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

20%

Explanation

As you see it's a thing which turns e.g. your empty roll of gift wrapping paper into a rocket launcher for New Year's Eve. Simply print it and put it on the top of the pipe of cardboard.
If you want you can add a view things like I've done.
I've cut the pipe at the point where the rocket's fuse ends und put a pipe made of an old tin (which had some icetea in it quite a time ago) in it so I can stick them together. Than I bought a cheap DC converter from Ebay, printed this little plug und connected a little battery to it, so in the plug there are little sparks if I turn it on, which are made to set the fuse on fire. The other opportunity to fire it up is to pull out the fuse a bit throug the little hole I had made, so you can light it up outside the launcher. But these are only examples to tune the launcher. Have fun. :)

Im Prinzip ist dies nur ein Aufsatz für z.Bsp. eine leere Rolle Geschenkpapier, welche von Weihnachten übrig ist. Ihr könnt ihn also auf so eine Papprolle in der Mitte des Geschenkpapiers platzieren, und schwupps habt ihr einen Raketenwerfer für Silvesterraketen.
Natürlich könnt ihr in auch noch tunen, wie ich es z.Bsp. getan habe.
Ich habe die Rolle an der Stelle der Zündschnur der Rakete durchgeschnitten, und eine Röhre aus einer altern Blechdose gebaut und eingesetzt, um den Raketenwerfer auch wieder schließen zu können. Außerdem ist an dieser Stelle ein Loch, um die Zündschnur nach draußen zu verlegen. Dann habe ich noch einen Gleichstromwandler gekauft (gibt'S billig bei Ebay), um kleine Blitze zu erzeugen welche die Zündschnur auf Knopfdruck entzünden können. Dafür habe ich diesen Zündungsstecker moddeliert.
Allerdings gibt es natürlich noch tausen andere Möglichkeiten um so einen Raketenwerfer zu tunen und zu personalisieren, doch der Aufsatz ist der Grundstein. Also viel Spaß damit :)

description.text:
About

If you make this, please post pictures!

Uses an E3D titan as well as their V6 extruder. Info below on where to find quality clones for much cheaper.

Features 2 blower fans for "overkill" style cooling, a proximity sensor, cable management, and a modular lightweight design. Everything has quick connectors, so it can be taken apart and re-assembled very quickly. The only part "required" is the main plate, so if you don’t want to use a certain part it is not a problem. AKA nothing mounts to anything else other than the main plate.

The main plate has cavities for each of the nuts. They should press fit in and stay there. The ducting for the layer cooling fans is designed to press fit in place over the blower fans. This allows easy removal and placement so you can add your own designs depending on the print requirements.

By using a modular design, you can not only easily remove parts for servicing / adjustment, but you can also add other tools such as a laser engraver, pen plotter, or vinyl cutter.

If you want to know more info, want the model files in a different format, or want small modifications, please let me know.

Parts

I used an E3D titan clone available from here. So far it seems to work perfectly. Trianglelab seems to actually care about quality. The dimensions are identical.

Pancake motor.

Upgraded thumb wheel

40W Heater cartraige

NTC 2950

V6 Clone

The Rep Rap champions clone is great except for the heartbreak, so order a better one from here or direct from E3D

Silicone Socks These are needed to prevent the powerful blower fans from quickly cooling the hot end.

Blower fans

Extruder fan

NPN LJ12A3-4-Z/BX proximity sensor As long as you get NPN, you will NOT need a resistor.

Dupont Connector Kit

Dupont crimper

Your cable of choice. I used unshielded Cat6

Various small wood screws as well as metric bolts / nuts from ACE hardware. I recommend printing this and then bringing into ACE or whatever your local hardware store is to find the right sizing. The wood screws are only used in places where there is no expectation of future removal.

This is a stand for the X1M Pro HF radio. It can be purchased (in the US) here: http://www.wouxun.us/item.php?item_id=302 First attempt at a stand for this radio. I like the way this particular design fits together without hardware and packs mostly flat. Version 1 didn't work beyond the initial modelling phase, this is Version 2. Version 2 didn't take into account that I was measuring from platform, not the upper portion of the back. Version 3 corrects this. Bars remain unchanged. Version 3 works! I'm going to see how ergonomic it is, and possibly change the overall height in another version. For now, it's finished.

Filament roll holder

Filament roll holder is mounted on an aluminum profile 20x40 groove 5, and serves for feeding my 3D printer. Filament roll holder can take the rolls of different widths. The width of the roll is adjusted with the lengths of spacer bushes.
Mounted by 2 M5 screws.
Filament roll holder consists of:

  1. Axle holder
  2. 4 wheels
  3. 2 steel axles, 90 mm long and 6 mm in diameter
  4. 4 spacer bushes, 10x6 13 mm long
  5. 4 O-rings, for the wheels fixation
    Positions 1,2 and 4 were printed on the 3D Printer.
    Position 3, 2 steel axles, I have excluded from an old color printer and sawed on necessary lengths. The source of axles is not that important, even an old nail can be taken if the diameter fits.
    The spacer bushes have no play and sit quite firmly on the waves.
    The axles are slightly pressed into the axle holder. If necessary, there are 4 threaded holes M3, for axle fixation.
    The wheels should be expressed at low speeds, since the axiality of the wheels is very important.

title: Laminar Flow Fountain Head with Garden Hose Threads

description.text: 3/22/2014 Update  ::  Removed Cap with tapered nozzle -- that, as was pointed out, was another source of turbulence.  I have uploaded instead a very much working 20mm nozzle with straight sides.  That is the cap shown in yellow with the nice flow in the latest photos.  Thanks to everyone for the tips and discussion and keeping this going.

I was inspired by this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ijn98G0I99E video. Laminar flow also has a wiki entry: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laminar_flow It seemed like a good project to attempt to design and 3d print. Simple but with several threaded pieces that were mostly a challenge to design -- they printed REALLY well. This all screwed together with ease. I am hoping that others will print and refine this model -- it works, but I am sure it could work even better. I would like to eventually make an illuminated one.

You need to print:
1 cap ( .3 layers 60% infill 3 perimeters)
1 Tube ( .3 layers 60% infill 3 perimeters)
1 Bottom Cap with GHT (.3 layers 60% infill 3 perimeters)
2 baffles (no top/bottom solids, 20% infill. 5 Perimeters) I plan to print just the rings for the baffle and use a piece of commercial nylon screen I think instead -- the whole idea is to reduce turbulence and my baffle seems like it creates it. I think a finer screen will result in a better stream. I used ZenToolworks ABS (Clear/transparent) for the majority of the design (all the white/translucent pieces) and ZenToolworks yellow ABS for some of the later caps.

well... you suggested multiple nozzles before my design was complete so it was a no-brainer. Silicone worked well. A slight smear on the flat mating surfaces was all it needed.

comments.author: Capitali

comments.text: I've tried three sizes of nozzle so far.. but all pitched.  I will try a straight one certainly.   The main cylinder I ended up printing turned out kind of unexpected, it's basically hollow between two shells but narrows @ the top for the threads and thickens at the bottom.  I believe I had the infill set too low on that one.  There is leakage under pressure at threads threads, but none in the vertical tube. Interestingly water does fill the hollow space between the shells eventually.  I think some teflon plumbers tape would seal the threads.
comments.author: Terminus

comments.text:
Your wall thickness of around 4mm won't be a problem for me. Afinia software automatically applies infill and does a very good job of it in general. It has problems filling very thin walls near 1.2mm (~0.06) or less, and instead prints two paper thin inner / outer layers. But anything thicker is either solid or gets max infill.
OTOH, tube length is a problem as this thing only prints a 5.5 inch cube...but that's no biggee.. I plan on remixing it to 3 separate sections in any case, and it'll probably end up longer than yours.

title: RC Jeep JK Chassis complete scale RC Car kit 1/10

description.text:
I needed a second chassis for my Hong Kong Jeep JK Body. Not for heavy crawling but for onroad and a little bit of offroad activities.

Last Update: 05-02-2018 (Details see below)

I used some second hand rails and copied them. Later I saw that they are made by Karnegie in the US (SSR V2). Some modifications are made to fit the Jeep body and the motor mount. The gear reducer unit can be found here http://www.rcmodelex.com/www-rcmodelex-com/eshop/18-1-Transmissions/0/5/1080-MEX-G-BOX-7-4-1-BLACK-5mm

The servo is in the rails so that a lot of axles can be used. I tried it with RC4WD Yota II Clones, Axial SCX10 II Clones and MST CMX axles.

There are three different Versions for the Transmission:

  • A - Simple 1:1 Transmission together with an RC Modelex Gear Reducer > See Pictures
  • B - RC4WD R2 Transmission
  • D - Axial SCX10 Transmission (untestet 2018-02-05)

Updates:

2018-02-05
Version D:
Added an untested Front Motor Mount for the Axial SCX10 Standard Transmission (eg. this one https://tamico.de/Axial-AX30487-Getriebe-Starr-Locked-AX10-SCX10). It is an improved Remix of one of my own Designs https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2588587
It offers space for an ESC and a Receiver (if you want to mount it close to the ESC)
I will add some pictures after printing

Pls. tell me how it works.

2018-02-04
1) For the ESC (Hobbywing 1080 30x35mm) and Receiver (24x52mm) I made two Boxes to store them away (not waterproof).
2) To place the Battery under the Backseats I lowered the back Brace (as low as Possible withe my Setup (Cantilever and CMX-Axle)).
3) To make it more rigid I added to Files that make that keep the distance between Body and Chassis. The front-one also provides space for some wires.

2018-01-25
I added a front Mount for the JK Body that uses the stock mounting holes.

2018-01-22
2 more front Rails uploaded. These rails have more holes to mount the shocks. So you can use longer ones or bring the body lower. Helpful if you use it togeher with the cantilever suspension.

2018-01-18
Uploaded 2 additional Rear Rails for Version A because for 313mm Wheelbase the last hole of the Shockmount is needed. I cuted it off to make the JK Body fit with no modifications.

2018-01-13:
After an Info from FourDogs that the rails have to be bent if you use Version A. I added to new Files with a reduced width:
Motor Mount:73.5 mm to 70.1 mm
Servo Mount:69 mm to 67 mm

2018-01-05: Update for a different Suspension (see link below)

  • C - Rear Rails for a Cantilever-Style-Suspension

The STL-Files are marked A,B,C and AB; AB means you need it for all Versions.
If you use Option C you also need the AB Parts

With the body mount (better print in PETG because of flexibility) you can easyly clip the body and chassis togehter. The clip needs two M3 10-16mm screws and stock holes of the body.

You might want to strenghen the Chassis. That e.g. can be done with the SCX10 brace parts. Most of them fit. Since 2018-04-02 you also can use the parts I made to make the Chassis more rigid.

If you make a chassis pls. let me know and show it as a "make" and if there are parts to be improved let men know. For me ist working fine at the moment :-)

The Parts for the Cantilever-Style Suspension can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2747093

Here are some more Things for the HK Jeep JK Body I made.

  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2616002 > Siderails V3
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2477104 > Siderails V1
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2614647 > Tube Doors
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2610266 > Wheel Cases
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2790987 > Rims for Jeep JK 10th Anniversary Edition

Printer:

Anet A6

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15-0.2

Infill:

25%-50%

Notes:

Some Parts are printed with 0.15mm for optical reasons. Usually I use 0.2mm
The Shell has 3 Perimeters and the Infill varies between 25% and 50%, depending on the required strengh of the part.

Maybe drilling some Holes

Some of the holes might be drilled again.
Because of very little Support needed there is almost no need to work after printing.

description.text:
I made these as the 3d printed blocks I had caused too much binding. These allow you to secure the IGUS bushing with 2 zip ties, rather than completely encompassing it.

The 2 versions present are as follows:

AnetA8BedIgusBlocks.stl: The version i have printed and am currently using. It works well, the bearings are held securely. The bed is a few mm higher than what i had, but I'm fine with that.

AnetA8BedIgusBlocksV2.stl: For added security, for those who are concerned about a bearing popping out, this should block them in, at either end, whilst they are secured with zip ties.

AnetA8BedIgusBlocksV3.stl: AS per the update below, i have added in a part that should hit the end stop instead of the bearing and keep things positioned correctly. I have also decreased the side of the mounting screw holes to ensure a tight fit when screwing - this can always be drilled out if they are too tight.

Note: I haven't printed AnetA8BedIgusBlocksV2.stl so not 100% sure if it works as intended.

I printed them on end and opted to not use supports as any Odd shaped holes helped the screws bite. A bit of super glue helped ensure this.

UPDATE 01/01/2018:

Just an FYI - I have found out that this has altered the position of my print bed, the Y end stop used to crash into the lower part of the block, however this is not on this model, which means that the bed goes back a few mm further until the bearing knocks it. This isn't a major issue if you never use your full Y dimension, or if you can alter your firmware. However on a stock A8 I believe this to be an issue. To this end, i have included V3, which should sort this out however as of this date I haven't had a change to test this yet. Let me know if it works!

description.text:
Camera Mount designed for vibration dampening, VTX/LED strip holder, and 30.5x30.5mm to 20x20mm flight controller mount for the BeeRotor 180 Frame.

Read my full build guide here: https://nathan.vertile.com/blog/2017/12/27/omnibus-nox-flight-controller-180mm-build/

The camera mount should work with any board cam with 2 small holes in the front on either side of the lens, for example: http://bit.ly/2zMLGkp

Any small, flat VTX will work, such as: http://bit.ly/2liGoJ6

Any 10-led RGB led strip should work, such as: http://bit.ly/2CqIoq0

Any flight controller will work, but the offset flight controller mount is designed to leave enough space for the NOX flight controller.

You'll need:
2x 2mm (3-5mm length) screws to attach the Camera to the mount
2x 2mm (3-5mm length) screws to attach the LED strip to the mount
8x 3mm (3-5mm length, depending on frame and flight controller thickness) screws to mount the flight controller

I added supports with Mesh Mixer and printed it vertically in PETG with .2mm layer height and 4 walls

title: MakerFarm 8" 3mm Borosilicate Glass Bed Leveling Corners

description.text:
I recently switched from hand cut 1/4 inch plate glass to 200 mm X 213 mm X 3 mm Borosilicate Glass Bed and needed better corner clamps to hold the glass & bed heater in place and accommodate easy leveling. My 1/4 inch plate glass plates kept chipping out of the face of the print surface leading to lumpy prints on the base. I print with ABS so I'm guessing all the heating and cooling got to the glass. The corners are contoured underneath to mate with both the glass bed and the heating bed, holding everything in nice, neat proximity.

Doesn't hurt to {Split} and {Auto Arrange} in Slicer. Give your printer an easier time of it...

comments.text: why do you have cork board under your build plate?
comments.author: danman24

comments.text: The cork insulates the build plate from the aluminum carriage that everything is mounted to. All the heat is directed into the bed. AL is a great conductor of heat (used for heat sinks in fact) so keeping it away from the heating element plate is a good idea. I think on many printers they use a piece "fire blanket" that serves the same purpose. The cork has held up well for a year and a half now!

description.text:
Recently I printed a rear mount extruder fan shroud and this newly printed one do hit my previous version of cable chain https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2221459. thus I redesign my cable chain to be horizontal, resize all chain link and mount to make sure nothing hit the chain.

NOTE
This particular bed mount do mount onto the Y-axis plate instead of the heated bed, making use of the square cut hole on the plate. You insert it into the square hole and it clip to it and also latch onto the edge of the plate. If the square cut hole doesn't exist on your Maker Select v2.1 Y-axis plate, then this mount isn't for you.

Also, the rear mount do extended the printer about 8cm in length. Measure before you print !!

title: Minimalist Quick Install Filament Box Outlet

description.text:
Update :: 2018.01.05 - I build a more complicated angled feed version.
at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2747899

Original Post :
When I built my Filament Dry Box, I came across several options on the filament guide out of the box, and they seem to be over complicated took a long time to install.

So I designed a simpler one that just required an insert and a lock ring to screw on.

The minimal you need is the lockring and the insert to print a working model. Drill a 10mm hole and you can simply tighten the lockring around the insert and you're done. The hole on the insert can take a 4mm OD PTFE tube to reduce friction but it's optional.

The cap is also optional, it might be useful to close it up and make it airtight. Note the cap is designed to be longer so that some of the filament can still be inside the cap to make it easier to pull out when you need it.

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

33%

Notes:

I used 0.8mm walls and I tried both 0.175mm and 0.2mm layer height and they both worked.

I just happened to use 33% infill just in case.

You only need to drill a 10mm or a 3/8" hole in the box to make the insert fit.

Note the thread is a ISO Metric Trapezoidal 10mm x 2mm commonly known as TR10x2 in case you want to custom build another cap or attachment.

The filament I used is eSun PLA+ which is slightly more flexible than a regular PLA.

Check your tolerances to make sure the lockring will fit. And if your printer is reasonably well maintained, it should work.

It takes 10 minutes in fusion360 to build this.

Just use circle with center at origin.
10mm
16mm
4mm
4.5mm

Extrude the parts as needed using the circles and create the threads using ISO Metric Trapezoidal. 10mm x2

title: Bowden clamp with holder for electronics

description.text:
Bowden clamp for Ultimaker prevents popping out PTFE tube.
It has holder for thermocouple circuit.
With short tube thread for those who cuted few time PTFE tube and now head want go in 0,0 position because of short tube.

I made this with holder for electr. for those who want to have thermocouple board and Bowden clamp together. Good thing with this design is for those who few times cuted PTFE tube and now head is not going to 0,0 position because of shorten tube. I assume that you dont need specialy manual how to mount , because your tube poped many times, and you did this many times :D :lol: First at all pull the tube through the nut !
Next you must mount thermocouple board - nuts goes in position at the bottom of the base
Then you can mount tube in white clamp and put blue clip
After that you can assemble the base. Since circuit board is large dimensions, all is made that suit in milimeter.
Mounting is with existing bolts. I printed all this in 0,1mm and it holds the tube like hell.
Thread of nut is also new, so I assume that you cant use old, but before printing you can check if it suits.

title: Universal Phone Stand (even for large phones)

description.text:
What do you do when you are bored? I just design some things...
This time I designed a simple smartphone stand that can be used with small and large phones. My Samsung A5 with attached bumper (5.2") fits nicely and even my large Nexus 6P (5.7") does not fall over. The maximum allowed phone thickness is 10mm.

I made three versions of this stand:

  • The small one will print on small printers with a build space of 100x100x100 (e.g. Fabrikator II Mini). But then an USB connector will not fit under the stand.
  • The large one needs a build space of 100x100x120 and then there should be enough space for an USB connector under your phone.
  • The extra large one needs a build space of 130x130x140 and is meant for tablets.

This thing must be printed with support.

UPDATE:
I added some new files with an 'antiroll' feature.
With the old version it is possible to tip your phone over if you hit the upper part of your phone really hard. The new antiroll version prevents that.
However I prefer the cleaner look of the old version without antiroll...

comments.text: Had an issue with it breaking in 4 places when removing the supports. What infil % did you use?

comments.text:
I am printing it with 25% infill and 0.2mm layers.
Fastest and most stable print will be if you lay it on its right or left side.

title: Moana - Heart of TeFiti - Simplified and Merged

description.text: Printed one of the originals of these for my niece for Christmas which turned out great, but saw in the comments someone asking for a joined version to print vertically. So I ran it through MeshLab to greatly reduce it's complexity, joined the halves in TinkerCad, and after some trial and error had a version that's 5x smaller in filesize, and seems to have printed relatively well on it's side with a brim and supports, though lost a little detail on the side I had down.

Had to do a little clean-up of the brim area with x-acto knife and some sandpaper after taking off the supports and brim, probably would have been better with a raft.

title: SCALEPRINT PALLBEARERS AND CASKET 00 HO SCALE
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Here we have the another of many scale figures I have created for my 00 train layout.
The figures are firstly put together in MakeHuman setting up the armature and clothing, and a basic pose.
I then import into blender to get the final pose that I require, I do this by importing other items that will be used by the final printed figure. This ensures the figure will fit the the surrounding items correctly.
The figure's were posed so that the hands hold the casket correctly and stand correctly on the stairs.
Their are 2 caskets one with the hockey sticks the other is plain.
Finally imported into my CAD software where I convert everything into solids, and orientated the model on the supports to be printed.
Models have support structure as part of the stl.

PLEASE NOTE THE BISHOP IS NOT PART OF THIS THINGY WAS DOWNLOADED FROM SCANS OF THE WORLD AND MODIFIED TO SUIT MY NEEDS

Printer:

WANHOA D7

Resolution:

0.035mm layer height

Notes:

This model was printed on a Wanhoa D7 using Monocure standard grey resin.
Have to set printer to your resin

comments.text: I am using a Wanhoa D7 resin printer for these. I used Monocure grey resin with 4 base layers at 120 seconds with a layer height of 0.050mm and the rest of 0.035mm at 50 seconds, but this will vary from printer to printer and resin to resin

description.text:
This remix is for a K40 with wheels. I changed the design, so that the threaded bar does not protrude from the bed and cutting area is not wasted.

The bottom holder contains a 8mm nut to hold the threaded rod and is screwed to the bottom with M4 screws. The timing pulley is fastened to the rod and with a ball bearing mounted to the top holder. The belt is tensioned fairly tight with cable ties.

I printed the parts with 25% infill and support.

From home depot:

  • 15x15mm steel square tube (2x15cm and 2x28cm)
  • expanded metal 50x25cm
  • M8 threaded rod + nut

From Ali:

  • 8x16x5mm ball bearing https://www.aliexpress.com/item/10PCS-LOT-Ball-Bearing-688-ZZ-688-2Z-688-2RS-688-2RZ-688-DDU-8x16x5-mm/32833410716.html
  • Pulley https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Reprap-CNC-Idler-Pully-without-teeth-2GT-timing-pulley-with-ball-bearing-3D-printer-for-6mm/32805017992.html
  • Timing pulley https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1-piece-20-teeth-Bore-8mm-GT2-Timing-Pulley-fit-width-6mm-of-2GT-timing-Belt/32736384491.html
  • Belt https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-Shipping-1PCS-LOT-GT2-1140-closed-loop-rubber-2GT-timing-belt-1140-GT2-6-Teeth/32791435275.html

title: 1cm radius disk with M3 hole in the middle

description.text:
For my delta, the top pulley are supposed to be comprised of a flanged bearing. However, I had a bunch of 9mm diameter x 4mm wide bearings with m3 holes in the middle, which fit the bill with the exception of missing flanges.  
I created a flanged spool that lets you slide in the bearings, but have come up with something simpler. These simple discs with M3 holes in the middle.  
I printed out 6 of them at 100% infill. They are 1cm in radius, 1mm thick, and have an M3 hole in the center.  
Basically insert them in, add two of the 4mm wide bearings, and add on in at the end. Now you have flanges up to prevent the belt from slipping off of the bearings.   
I made sure the smooth side(side on the tape during printing) is facing toward the belt.

• Print at 100% infill
  • Install on either side of the simple bearings to serve as a flange/wall
  • Add nuts to the outside to ensure they stay against the bearings
  • Install belt
  • Done

comments.text:
If you have a well tuned printer and can print perfect circles, you can make use of this model that encloses the bearings in a flanged pulley:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:296045http://www.thingiverse.com/thi...

title: Dual Extruder for CR-10 one or two E3D
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This setup is a side by side configuration. My old ones are now replaced with this since it has several updated things that make it much easier to set the correct height between the extruders. Something that can be a pain in the b... as you might know.

It uses the original extruder and the original fan for it. The fan is mounted with dubble sided tape on the fan holder.

The set screw is now on back so the E3D doesn't have do be removed. A set screw on top to help with tiny adjustments. And the radial fan has a more secure holding to prevent from rotating. It is a nut in-bedded in the E3D holder so it can be harder tightened. There are in fact several M3 nuts in-bedded in the construction so that the threads doesn't wear out.

To find the exact offset in X and Y do like this. Put some painters tape on the heat bed and lower the nozzles by hand so the press slightly against the tape. The push the bed in X and Y direction. The nozzle will leave a faint mark on the tape. Just measure with a caliper between center and center of respectively track marks. Put this where you find good use for it.

180109: Files with name "E3D Mount2XE3D" are extra for changing the original hotend to another E3D. I noticed that an hotend that is like the original is almost twice the price of one E3D clone so there is no reason to by an "original" version if it breaks.
The fan holder for the right hotend has to be slightly modified so it is possible to rotate it. Just to remove a small portion of it.

Tinkercad

This thing is an insert for the pegboard double ring holders. Even though it looks quite different, I wrote this code based on the "Pegboard hex driver adaptor" thing #1727845 by CyFire.

I've always found these double ring holders to be quite useless because the rings are too large and it's easy to miss both rings when trying to insert a tool.

With the customizer, you can an make an insert that will both fit the double ring and the tool perfectly. I have provided an example STL file that fits the double rings pegboard holder I have, but more than likely, you'll have to customize the design to fit your holder.

title: TronXY X5S Improved / Modified Marlin Firmware

description.text:
This is a modified version of the stock Marlin 1.1.6dev firmware for the TronXY X5S.

I have made many small improvements.

Manual Mesh Leveling added. 4x4 matrix
Improved homing , and jog speeds from LCD , particularly Z axis. Stock 4mm/s is far to slow
Increased Z max speed. 4mm/s is far to slow to prevent blobbing during Z moves. Max is now 35mm/s
Much improved encoder operation. It now works as expected. Single click for menu items, proper direction, and better multiplier operation when changing values.
EEPROM support enabled.
Filament change options enabled.
Better default Jerk settings.
Proper MAX positions.

Several other small changes.

Minus having to run bed leveling the first time...this is a drop in replacement. Flash and dash....

I suggest executing a "RESTORE FAILSAFE" from the LCD to ensure proper default EEPROM values are loaded immediately after flashing.

Enjoy!

author: dannytheboss9

title: Pegboard Pass-Through Socket Organizer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
• Good news: I got my new Bostitch Pass-Through Socket set (BTMT72286)
  • Bad news: No easy way to hang it on my pegboard!

tl;dr: Teenage son built the models you can download. If you like them, he'll take donations to his High School Robotics club. If you hate them, he'll still take donations. :P Feel free to either PayPal me here and I'll pass it through, or figure out how to donate to Perry High School Robotics (Arizona)

Details

Overview

This is the solution. I asked my 16 year old son to 3D print me a set that could hang on my pegboard, and have a magnetic back. Now, like all 16-year old son's, that didn't happen immediately, so I built one in SketchUp. Then, he built one that was better, in less time. These are those designs.

Materials

  • 3D Printer (in our case a Creality3D CR-10)
  • PLA filament (we used Hatchbox)
  • Magnets. I bought the Magnet Source magnets from Home Depot. Home Depot doesn't have a link to them online, but I have the photo below with the packaging. They are the NR007403N. Dimensions are: 18.8mm OD, 9.53 mm ID, 2.67mm thick

Process

  • He started in Autodesk Inventor with a hexagon. We knew we wanted a place for the magnets on the backside, so created a hole with a center post for that. We wanted the center post to limit the amount of printing happening "in the air" so we could go without supports that needed to be cleaned up.
  • He printed a single on his Creality3D CR - 10 (that he bought himself!) and we tested. Good overall fit. The hole for the magnet a little too small. Version 2 fixed that, and he chamfered the edges on the socket side to allow the sockets to slide in easier.
  • Then he ensured the wall thickness was enough to allow for them to stack with enough space between the sockets and copied them into blocks of 8 and 9. Added a small hexagon hole at the top for a pegboard peg to go through, and then printed.
  • Update: Actually, it's a 10 and 7, which I didn't notice until I lined them up and saw that they put the 10mm on the SAE side. Brilliant. I've decided not to reprint.
  • Print time for a single block was about 30 minutes, it was a few hours for the entire holder.
  • The magnets are simply Neodymium Ring Magnets, available from Home Depot/Lowes, and fit in the back as seen. You'll want to glue them in.
  • The Bostitch set I got was 21 pieces. It's not obvious, but that means 8 of one socket size and 9 of another, so both models are attached.
  • Notes: When printing these there was one socket that was tight. As a result, he created two different sets of files, one with more tolerance, and one with less (i.e. it's tighter). If you use the magnets, more tolerance works out awesome.

Conclusion

When I looked online it looked like single line socket holders (none of which worked for pass-through sockets) were about $8 a piece. So, I paid him $10 per socket holder, plus $5 for his time (for a total of $25), since we used the materials he has bought and the machine he had bought, plus the skills he's developed. Fun father/son project.

Finished picture first. Final set, hanging on pegboard Single block, socket side. Single socket inserted Backside of set with magnets glued in Both sets (8 & 9) side by side, with one removed

print_settings.Notes:: I've included a file for a gem shape that I originally intended to attach to the lid handle and print it in an emerald green filament, but I ran out of time, and I thought the handle looked good as is.

description.text:
My father is retired and in his spare time he makes jewelry boxes. He's been fascinated by 3D printing, and so I thought it would be cool to learn Fusion 360 to design and print a jewelry box to give to my mom for Christmas. It turned out great, she loved it, he thought it was the coolest thing ever, and I got to learn Fusion 360.

The box is meant to be printed in separate parts and glued together. This allows you to have multiple colors or materials and makes it easier to print. The box is ~160x100x50mm.

I've included the Fusion 360 file in case you'd like to make some changes.

Please post your makes if you decide to print one.

Printer:

Wilson TS

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 layer height, 0.6 nozzle, 2 shells.

Infill:

15% grid

Notes:

I chose to print the box in Spools3D wood fill filament. It turned out really nicely, especially after some sanding. The embossing on the sides has been designed so that any parts that overhang too much have been chamfered or have a stepped support underneath and should print easily with adequate cooling. Printing time was about 6 hours at 60mm/s

The lid top was printed in the same wood filament. I used 4 perimeters in order to give more support to the terracing, but you can make adjustments to suit your aesthetic tastes. I used the concentric top infill pattern as well to give it a bit of visual impact.

The lid base was printed with the narrow part facing down so that the underside of the lid had a nice glassy surface, but you could also flip it around if your printer has trouble with overhangs. I chose AMZ3D gold PLA at 0.1 layer height. Printing time was about 1 hour.

The lid handle was printed in Polyalchemy Elixir Abyss at 0.1 layer height. It's a rather small part, so pay attention to minimum layer time and ensure good cooling and appropriately slow speeds. Printing time was about 45 minutes.

I've included a file for a gem shape that I originally intended to attach to the lid handle and print it in an emerald green filament, but I ran out of time, and I thought the handle looked good as is.

I used gel superglue to attach the lid top and lid base. The gel gives me enough working time to get the base centered before it sets.

The lid top has a cut out shape for the lid handle. You may need to clean up the edges a bit to get it to fit. It should be fairly snug. I ended up trimming off a bit of the bottom edge of the handle part and it fit perfectly. Use superglue to secure it.

Since I used wood filament I wanted to see how well it would sand. I used an 80 and 120 grit foam pads and sanded the rounded edges until the layer lines were gone. It left a very smooth and soft surface. I didn't try staining it, but would really like to see how that would turn out.

I used this as a project to learn Fusion 360 as well. A few YouTube videos later, and I was on my way. Lars Christensen has a great channel with lots of tutorials. I recommend anyone interested in learning Fusion 360 give it a try. https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCo29kn3d9ziFUZGZ50VKvWA

I started with a box shape using the golden ratio, and started adding some filets and chamfers, and sketched out some art deco designs on the sides as embossments.

description.text:
Was inspired by this model: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2681295

This GPU stand is designed with a rear support so the card isn't simply hanging. Its also go a central bridge for even more support under the PCIe Riser. The riser stand slips into holes that are 20mm x 5mm in case I decide to expand on use. The riser bridge can be removed and upgraded. The front supports mounting of a 120mm fan. Holes are spaced for 105mm x 105mm. I modeled the holes for use with a noctua anti vibration pegs in case I didn't want to use screws. I wanted these to interlock so I could add more in the future without them sliding around. If you have any suggestions on upgrades or addons, feel free to let me know and I'll see what I can do.

Update:
v8 has been uploaded. Includes rear interlocks as well as extenders for use to mount these back to back. Extended Rear riser brace.
